\section{The College of Celestial Magics (Ver 1.1)}
d19 3
d23 10
a32 12
of the college, and may only change divisions by forsaking their
present division, hence losing all of their current magical
knowledge, and undertaking at least six months training in the new
division of the College.

Creatures' fear of the power of the celestial aspect opposing their
own gives this college special power.  Hence the fright table \S
\ref{tables:frighttable} must be rolled on as a result of certain
spells.  A Magical Aptitude of 14 is required to learn the General
Knowledge of this college.  Note also that certain spells of this
college may only be learnt by specific divisions (as listed after the
Spell Number).
d39 1
a39 5
Solar and Star Mages use the element of light, and Shadow Weavers and
Dark Mages use the element of darkness.  The bonuses and penalties
gained in this section apply to non-magical forms of this element.
Magical forms of the element may at best neutralise any penalties
suffered due to the natural element.
d41 2
d61 14
a74 88
\subsubsection{Solar and Dark Mages}

Solar and Dark Mages are affected by the relative presence of their
element in their vicinity.  Note that for the purposes of these
modifiers the vicinity is deemed to be any bounded area around the
adept (e.g., a room), or, if in the open, the area within 30 feet of
the adept.  Two factors need to be taken into account when attempting
to decide on the a rate modifier: the quality of the light (bright or
dim); and the extent of the light (evenly distributed or lots of
shadows).  Although there is no inherent difference between natural
and artificial light, in general artificial light is of poorer
quality.  Note that because of the purity of direct sunlight it has
special powers against certain of the Greater Undead.

\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{c@@{\hspace{0.5em}}cX}
{\bf Light}	&  {\bf Mod}	& {\bf Example} \\
1\%		& -25		& Inside an attic or cellar \\
5\%		& -20		& ... with a small hole \\
10\%		& -15		& Overcast night \\
25\%		& -10		& Clear moonless night \\
40\%		& -5		& Night of the full moon \\
50\%		& 0		& Twilight (dusk or dawn) \\
60\%		& 5		& Bright day in a forest \\
75\%		& 10		& Overcast day \\
90\%		& 15		& Partly cloudy day \\
95\%		& 20		& Bright sunny day \\
00\%		& 25		& Totally light, no shadows \\
\end{tabularx}

\smallskip

\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{c@@{\hspace{0.5em}}cX}
{\bf Dark}	&  {\bf Mod}	& {\bf Example} \\
1\%		& -25		& Daytime in a desert \\
5\%		& -20		& Small shadows about \\
10\%		& -15		& Brightly lit interior \\
25\%		& -10		& Brightly lit underground \\
40\%		& -5		& Overcast day in a gorge \\
50\%		& 0		& Inside on an overcast day \\
60\%		& 5		& Torch-lit underground \\
75\%		& 10		& Shuttered room \\
90\%		& 15		& Windowless room \\
95\%		& 20		& Candle in total darkness \\
00\%		& 25		& Pitch-black darkness \\
\end{tabularx}

Note that the Dark examples can be applied conversely to a Solar Mage,
and vice versa.  For example, 10\% light (an overcast night), is
equivalent to 90\% dark (a windowless room).

\subsubsection{Shadow Weavers}

Shadow Weavers are affected by the shadows in their vicinity.  Note
that for the purposes of these modifiers the vicinity is deemed to be
any bounded area around the adept (e.g., a room), or, if in the open,
the area within 30 feet of the adept.  There are three cumulative
factors that must be taken into account: whether the adept is standing
within a shadow or not; how far away the edge of the shadow is from
the adept; and how well-defined the shadow is.  Each of the factors
must be included once and only once, and the second two factors must
relate to the same shadow.  The size of the shadow must be sufficient
to totally contain the adept in order to use it for these modifiers.
Neither their own shadow, nor the shadow created by anything they are
wearing can be used for these modifiers.  If no such shadow exists in
the vicinity (that is the distance is 30'+ ) then the Quality of
Contrast modifier must be ``No contrast''.

\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{Xr}
{\bf Location}		& {\bf Mod} \\
In light		& -10 \\
Partly in shadow	& 0 \\
In shadow		& +10 \\
\end{tabularx}

\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{Xr}
{\bf Distance From Boundary}	& {\bf Mod} \\
0' to 5'		& +5 \\
16' to 30'		& -5 \\
30' +			& -10 \\
\end{tabularx}

\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{Xr}
{\bf Quality of Contrast}& {\bf Mod} \\
Sharp contrast		& +5 \\
Good contrast		& 0 \\
Poor contrast		& -5 \\
No contrast		&-10 \\
\end{tabularx}
d76 2
a77 37
For example, if shadow weavers stand 10' inside a cave on a sunny day,
the modification they would receive on their spells would be +15,
(+10, 0, and +5 modifiers respectively).  Moving towards the entrance
would increase their modifier to +20, and then reduce it to +10 as
they crossed and then to 0 after crossing fully into the light.  If it
was an overcast day then all of those factors would be reduced by 10
(that is -5 for a poor contrast instead of a +5 for a sharp contrast).

\subsubsection{Star Mages}

Star Mages draw their power from light within darkness.  Hence there
is an ideal amount of light which will give them their best chance at
performing their arts. More light than this and the contrast is not
great enough; less light than this and they cannot draw enough power.
Note that it is the quality of light that is important.  Star Mages
are much better off with small bright light sources in darkness, than
with just evenly spread light such as an overcast day.

\bigskip

\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{@@{\hspace{0.5em}}c@@{\hspace{0.5em}}c@@{\hspace{0.5em}}X}
{\bf Light}	& {\bf Mod}	& {\bf Condition} \\
90\%		& -20		& Brightly lit underground \\
		&		& area / Full daylight \\
70\%		& -10		& In a shady forest / A \\
		&		& stormy day \\
50\%		& 0		& Indoors on a overcast day \\
		&		& / Dusk \\
25\%		& 5		& A fully torch-lit area / \\
		&		& Night of full moon \\
10\%		& 10		& Several lights in an under- \\
		&		& ground area / A normal night \\
8\%		& 10		& A bright lantern in the \\
		&		& dark / Clear moonless night \\
5\%		& 10		& A touch in total darkness \\
1\%		& 0		& A candle in total darkness \\
\end{tabularx}
d187 2
a188 2
suppressed. The volume will be 1000 (+ 500 / Rank) cubic feet, and
may be in any one contiguous area the Adept desires, provided that no
d190 14
a203 18
and within range at time of casting, and may not be moved.
At Ranks 0--5 the amount of darkness within the volume is reduced to
10\% (appears as though lit on a cloudy day), at Ranks 6--10 it is
reduced to 5\% (as though lit on a sunny day), at Ranks 11--15 it is
reduced to 1\% (similar to daytime in a desert), and at Ranks 16--20
all darkness is banished (i.e., totally light), so it is impossible to
see into or whilst within the volume (unless under the effects of a
Resistance to Light).  It will not aid in providing bonuses for
casting purposes, though it will reduces penalties due to natural
darkness by up to 5\% (+ 1\% / Rank). If the lighting conditions are
higher than that provided by the spell, no effect will be apparent.
Note that because darkness is being suppressed, no light is generated,
so any area outside the volume will not be lit. This spell can
engender silhouettes, though not create shadows. If it is not possible
to see to a lit volume, then objects within the volume are not
visible.  Any of this volume may be overridden by a higher ranked Spell
of Darkness, or neutralised (back to original conditions) by an equal
rank.
